What about SVM and linear reg
C is high mean high regularisation

C in sklearn is inversely proportional to regularisation term lambda used in formulation of L.R/SVM. If lambda is large then, you are penalizing your large weights more. Since, C is inversely proportional to lambda, high C would mean low lambda hence less regularisation i.e more chance your model overfits.
On the contrary, low C would mean high lambda hence more regularisation i.e your model underfits.
Please correct if I am wrong
C is not multiplied with the error term but the weights.
If you if you check svm: c is associated with the error term!

Well for SVM, things change slightly. But the whole idea still remains the same. If you have large C, lambda will be low i.e less regularisation so you will make less error on training data but your model won't generalize well and will overfit.
Conclusion: lower value of c will give more regularisation
In this case C that is used is actually 1/lambda

Interview question : why harmonic mean in F1 score why not normal mean. ?
to have less effect of outliers on the f1 score

We use the harmonic mean instead of a simple average because it punishes extreme values. A classifier with a precision of 1.0 and a recall of 0.0 has a simple average of 0.5 but an F1 score of 0. The F1 score gives equal weight to both measures and is a specific example of the general FÎ² metric where Î² can be adjusted to give more weight to either recall or precision.

Hi, in a binary classification problem, if I encounter some rows which has missing values for class variable, should I delete these rows as the most imp data isn't available or impute them with the mode?

There is no generalized answer to this question. If the proportion of missing values is less compared to your data size, you can get rid of them. If this is not true, you need to try multiple imputation techniques and find what gives the best results.
